{"questionId":"13916319","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The assumption that the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math> is constant is not correct. It can be shown that</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>98</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>14</mn></msup></mrow><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>41</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mi>s</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">Hence, the new model is given by</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>s</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>98</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>14</mn></msup></mrow><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>41</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mi>s</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>8</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">When <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>s</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>, it is known that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>If the model is correct, describe the shape of the graph of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi></math> against <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>g</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mfenced><mi>c</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>OR</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;gradient is a constant&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>so the graph should be a straight line&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"13916319","referenceCode":"23N.3.AHL.TZ0.1bi","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"If the model is correct, describe the shape of the graph of v against t.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.2—Increasing and decreasing functions","Topic 5—Calculus","AHL 5.10—Second derivatives, testing for max and min"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":3}
